We do not recommend directly to disable however it is known to conflict with several application or windows component and it is a good practice to disable in order to verify that this is conflicting. Then it is up to Cx to decide if maintain it disabled or investigate further.
 
To disable it we need to ensure that the policy is not applied and the following registries are set as here:
 
Set HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SYSTEM\CurrentControlSet\Control\DeviceGuard\Scenarios\CredentialGuard\Enabled =0
Set KEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\System\CurrentControlSet\Control\DeviceGuard\EnableVirtualizationBasedSecurity =0
Set HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SYSTEM\CurrentControlSet\Control\Lsa\LsaCfgFlags =0
 
In some cases if the setup was done with Uefi lock means that the Credential guard will be hardcoded in the Bios hence disabling it trough Gpo or registry fails
 


 
 
 
Verify with following Powershell command the status and also System information:
 

 
 
(Get-CimInstance -ClassName Win32_DeviceGuard -Namespace root\Microsoft\Windows\DeviceGuard).SecurityServicesRunning
 This command will display if the credential guard is enable or not
 
 
 

